04776nam a22007095i 9780292744349DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212013txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927443497 a10.7560/7443322doi  a(DE-B1597)588335  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aGN13.5b.U63 2013 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a301.02852231 aUnderberg, Natalie M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDigital Ethnography :bAnthropology, Narrative, and New Media /cElayne Zorn, Natalie M. Underberg. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (127 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER 1 Rethinking Culture through Multimedia Ethnography -- tCHAPTER 2 Florida and Peru: Experiments in Ethnographic Representation -- tCHAPTER 3 Digital Tools for Anthropological Analysis -- tCHAPTER 4 Using the Extensible Markup Language in Cultural Analysis and Presentation -- tCHAPTER 5 Using Features of Digital Environments to Enable Cultural Learning -- tCHAPTER 6 Cultural Heritage Video Game Design -- tConclusion: Narratives and Critical Anthropology: Roles for New Media -- tAPPENDIX Guide to Web- Based Materials -- tGlossary -- tReferences Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDigital ethnography can be understood as a method for representing real-life cultures through storytelling in digital media. Enabling audiences to go beyond absorbing facts, computer-based storytelling allows for immersion in the experience of another culture. A guide for anyone in the social sciences who seeks to enrich ethnographic techniques, Digital Ethnography offers a groundbreaking approach that utilizes interactive components to simulate cultural narratives. Integrating insights from cultural anthropology, folklore, digital humanities, and digital heritage studies, this work brims with case studies that provide in-depth discussions of applied projects. Web links to multimedia examples are included as well, including projects, design documents, and other relevant materials related to the planning and execution of digital ethnography projects. In addition, new media tools such as database development and XML coding are explored and explained, bridging the literature on cyber-ethnography with inspiring examples such as blending cultural heritage with computer games. One of the few books in its field to address the digital divide among researchers, Digital Ethnography guides readers through the extraordinary potential for enrichment offered by technological resources, far from restricting research to quantitative methods usually associated with technology. The authors powerfully remind us that the study of culture is as much about affective traits of feeling and sensing as it is about cognition—an approach facilitated (not hindered) by the digital age.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAnthropologyxComputer network resources. 0aCommunication in anthropology. 0aDigital communications. 0aDigital media. 0aDigital video. 0aVideo recording in ethnology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aMcDaniel, Rudy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUnderberg, Natalie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZorn, Elayne, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/74433240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292744349423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292744349/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SS